  "texts": [
    "Additionally, using a random algorithm ensures that the baseline does not exploit any specific features of the problem domain.",
    "This makes it an ideal control for benchmarking algorithms that are expected to leverage more sophisticated techniques, such as fitness functions or reward structures.",
    "Thus, the random algorithm serves as a \"null model\" that gives insight into how much the performance gains of the GA and RL methods stem from their structure and design, as opposed to mere chance in estimating WCET.The findings from both case studies, previously discussed in separate sections, are synthesized here to provide an evaluation.",
    "For random algorithm, in CD case study, 15 random numbers in the valid ranges were chosen at each step and the execution time was measured.",
    "For both the GA and RL methodologies, the top n results were stored, where n represents the size of the population in GA (100), which as mentioned in RQ2 section (5.3.2), the same amount of best execution times are stored for RL algorithms.To ensure a fair comparison between the random algorithm, GA, and RL, we followed a structured approach."
